
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `gzip` baraye feshrde (compress) kardan file-ha estefade mishavad. In kar حجم file-ha ra kam mikonad ta zakhireh kardan ya ferestadan asantar shavad. File-haye feshrde shode معمولاً پسوند `.gz` migirand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `gzip file.txt`  --> 📦 File `file.txt` ra feshrde mikonad va yek file jadid be name `file.txt.gz` misazad.
    🔹 `gzip -d file.txt.gz`  --> 🔓 File `file.txt.gz` ra baz mikonad va file asli `file.txt` ra bargardanad.
    🔹 `gzip -k file.txt`  --> 💾 File `file.txt` ra feshrde mikonad amma file asli ra negah midarad (پاک nemikonad).
    🔹 `gzip -l file.txt.gz`  --> 📊 Etela'at raje be andaze feshrde va gheyre feshrde file ra namayesh midahad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gzip myfile.log

    🔹 File `myfile.log` ra feshrde mikonad va آن ra be `myfile.log.gz` tabdil mikonad.

    $ gzip -d myfile.log.gz

    🔹 File `myfile.log.gz` ra baz mikonad va آن ra be `myfile.log` tabdil mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gzip -l myfile.log.gz
    compressed        uncompressed  ratio uncompressed_name
           12345             67890  82.0% myfile.log

    🔹  Neshan midahad andaze feshrde shode, andaze gheyre feshrde va درصد feshrde shodan file `myfile.log.gz` ra.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `gzip` command is used to compress files.  It reduces file size, making it easier to store and transfer. Compressed files usually have the `.gz` extension.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `gzip file.txt`  --> 📦 Compresses `file.txt` and creates a new file named `file.txt.gz`.
    🔹 `gzip -d file.txt.gz` --> 🔓 Decompresses `file.txt.gz` and restores the original file `file.txt`.
    🔹 `gzip -k file.txt` --> 💾 Compresses `file.txt` but keeps the original file (does not delete it).
    🔹 `gzip -l file.txt.gz` --> 📊 Displays information about the compressed and uncompressed size of the file.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gzip myfile.log

    🔹 Compresses the `myfile.log` file and converts it to `myfile.log.gz`.

    $ gzip -d myfile.log.gz

    🔹 Decompresses the `myfile.log.gz` file and converts it back to `myfile.log`.

✅ **Simple Example & Explanation:**

    $ gzip -l myfile.log.gz
    compressed        uncompressed  ratio uncompressed_name
           12345             67890  82.0% myfile.log

    🔹  Shows the compressed size, uncompressed size, and compression ratio of the `myfile.log.gz` file.
